  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2000_Solutions_2000s_page_001_2",
    "text": "A–1 The possible values comprise the interval (0, A2).",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.09333333333333334,
      0.16424242424242425,
      0.45098039215686275,
      0.1806060606060606
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2000_Solutions_2000s_page_001",
    "order": 3
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2000_Solutions_2000s_page_001_4",
    "text": "Pythagorean Theorem then shows that the rectangle P2P4P6P8 has sides √2 and 2√2. For notational ease, denote the area of a polygon by putting brackets around the name of the polygon.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.556078431372549,
      0.16545454545454547,
      0.92,
      0.22363636363636363
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2000_Solutions_2000s_page_001",
    "order": 4
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2000_Solutions_2000s_page_001_3",
    "text": "To see that the values must lie in this interval, note that",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.12627450980392158,
      0.18424242424242424,
      0.4886274509803922,
      0.2
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2000_Solutions_2000s_page_001",
    "order": 5
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2000_Solutions_2000s_page_001_7",
    "text": "By symmetry, the area of the octagon can be expressed as",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.5576470588235294,
      0.22787878787878788,
      0.9192156862745098,
      0.25636363636363635
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2000_Solutions_2000s_page_001",
    "order": 6
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2000_Solutions_2000s_page_001_5",
    "text": "s0 ∑j=0xj ≤ A2 − 2x0x1. Letting m → ∞, we have ∑j=0xj ≤ A2 − 2x0x1 < A2.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.12627450980392158,
      0.2642424242424242,
      0.4894117647058824,
      0.3006060606060606
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2000_Solutions_2000s_page_001",
    "order": 7
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2000_Solutions_2000s_page_001_8",
    "text": "Note that [P2P3P4] is √2 times the distance from P3 to P2P4, which is maximized when P3 lies on the midpoint of arc P2P4; similarly, [P4P5P6] is √2/2 times the dis- tance from P5 to P4P6, which is maximized when P5 lies on the midpoint of arc P4P6. Thus the area of the octagon is maximized when P3 is the midpoint of arc P2P4 and P5 is the midpoint of arc P4P6. In this case, it is easy to calculate that [P2P3P4] = √5 − 1 and [P4P5P6] = √5/2 − 1, and so the area of the octagon is 3√5.$",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.556078431372549,
      0.2963636363636364,
      0.92,
      0.44606060606060605
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2000_Solutions_2000s_page_001",
    "order": 8
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2000_Solutions_2000s_page_001_6",
    "text": "To show that all values in (0, A2) can be obtained, we use geometric progressions with x1 /x0 = x2/x1 = ·.. = d for ariabled. hen=0xj = x0(1−d) and",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.12627450980392158,
      0.30484848484848487,
      0.49098039215686273,
      0.3515151515151515
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2000_Solutions_2000s_page_001",
    "order": 9
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2000_Solutions_2000s_page_001_9",
    "text": "As d increases from 0 to 1, (1 − d)/(1 + d) decreases from 1 to 0. Thus if we take geometric progressions with ∑j=0xj = A, ∑j=0x2 ranges from 0 to A2. Thus the possible values are indeed those in the interval (O, A2), as claimed.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.12549019607843137,
      0.4175757575757576,
      0.49098039215686273,
      0.49333333333333335
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2000_Solutions_2000s_page_001",
    "order": 10
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2000_Solutions_2000s_page_001_10",
    "text": "A–4 To avoid some improper integrals at 0, we may as well replace the left endpoint of integration by some ε > 0. We now use integration by parts:",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.5231372549019608,
      0.45575757575757575,
      0.9192156862745098,
      0.5
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2000_Solutions_2000s_page_001",
    "order": 11
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2000_Solutions_2000s_page_001_11",
    "text": "A–2 First solution: Let a be an even integer such that a2 + 1 is not prime. (For example, choose a = 2 (mod 5), so that a2 + 1 is divisible by 5.) Then we can write a2 + 1 as a difference of squares x2 − b2, by factoring a2 + 1 as rs with r ≥ s > 1, and setting x = (r + s)/2, b = (r − s)/2. Final, put n = x2 −1, s0 that n = a2 + b2, n + 1 = x2, n +2 = x2 + 1.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.09411764705882353,
      0.503030303030303,
      0.49019607843137253,
      0.6048484848484849
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2000_Solutions_2000s_page_001",
    "order": 12
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2000_Solutions_2000s_page_001_12",
    "text": "Second solution: It is well-known that the equation x2 – 2y2 = 1 has infinitely many solutions (the so- called \"Pell\" equation). Thus setting n = 2y2 (so that n = y2 + y2, n + 1 = x2 + 02, n + 2 = x2 + 12) yields infinitely many n with the desired property.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.12549019607843137,
      0.6096969696969697,
      0.49019607843137253,
      0.683030303030303
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2000_Solutions_2000s_page_001",
    "order": 13
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2000_Solutions_2000s_page_001_14",
    "text": "1/x2. Thus it suffi ces to note that",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.5552941176470588,
      0.6266666666666667,
      0.92,
      0.6775757575757576
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2000_Solutions_2000s_page_001",
    "order": 14
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2000_Solutions_2000s_page_001_13",
    "text": "Third solution: As in the fi rst solution, it suffi ces to ex- hibit x such that x2 − 1 is the sum of two squares. We will take x = 32\", and show that x2 − 1 is the sum of two squares by induction on n: if 32n − 1 = a2 + b2, then",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.12627450980392158,
      0.6872727272727273,
      0.49098039215686273,
      0.7460606060606061
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2000_Solutions_2000s_page_001",
    "order": 15
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2000_Solutions_2000s_page_001_17",
    "text": "and that the fi nal integral converges absolutely by com- parison to 1/x3.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.556078431372549,
      0.7951515151515152,
      0.9192156862745098,
      0.8248484848484848
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2000_Solutions_2000s_page_001",
    "order": 16
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2000_Solutions_2000s_page_001_15",
    "text": "Fourth solution (by Jonathan Weinstein): Let n = 4k4 + 4k2 = (2k2)2 + (2k)2 for any integer k. Then n + 1 = (2k2 + 1)2 + 02 and n + 2 = (2k2 + 1)2 + 12.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.12549019607843137,
      0.816969696969697,
      0.49019607843137253,
      0.8624242424242424
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2000_Solutions_2000s_page_001",
    "order": 17
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2000_Solutions_2000s_page_001_19",
    "text": "An alternate approach is to first rewrite sin xsin x2 as 2(cos(x2 − x) − cos(x2 + x)). Then",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
